When a small group of living beings (a small population) separates from the main and original group (e.g., crossing a mountain range or a river, or migrating to a new island, and cannot go back) they will often find themselves in a mountain range of the old habitat the same way to each other than they were before.
This new environment has different resources and competitors, so the new population will need different characteristics or adaptations than they needed to be a strong competitor.
The original population has not changed at all and they still need the same adaptations as before.
Over time, as the new population starts to adapt to its new environment, it starts to look less and less like the other population.
Finally, after thousands or even millions of years, the years, the two populations were so different that they could no longer be considered the same species.
This process is called speciation, which means the formation of new species. Speciation is a consequence that cannot be avoided and a very important part of evolution.
