Technological determinism is a term that in practice encompasses a wide range of ideas, from the technological impulse or technological imperative to a strict sense that human destiny is guided by a hidden logic that is associated with the science of science and its manifestation in technology.
Most interpretations of technological determinism share two general ideas: that the development of technology itself follows a path largely beyond cultural or political influence, and that technology, at the same time, has "effects" on the same-sex of the societies that are inherent, rather than being socially conditioned.
For example, it could be said that motor cars necessarily lead to the development of roads.
However, a nationwide road network for a handful of cars is not economically viable, so new production methods are being developed to reduce the cost of having a car.
The possession of mass cars also leads to a greater incidence of road accidents, leading to the invention of new medical assistance techniques to repair damaged bodies.
